[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "An Overview of White’s 4th Moves"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E00"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41557201"]

1. d4 {[%cal Bd4e5,Bd4c5]} { The Queen's Pawn Opening. } Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} { This is the characteristic move of the various Indian Defenses (or “Indian games”) , so called because of the legacy to the game [https://www.chess.com/article/view/the-indian-roots-of-modern-chess] brought by the great predecessors of Anand and Gukesh. } 
2. c4 {[%cal Bc4d5]} { Controlling d5. } ( { We don't cover moves like } 2.Bf4 { , the London, } ) ( 2.Bg5 { , the Trompowsky, or } ) ( 2.Nf3 { , the Knights Variation (which can lead to the Torre Attack after 3.Bg5 or the Colle System after 3.e3, etc.) } ) e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} { Opening the Black's dark-squared bishop diagonal and challenging White's ambition in the center. } 
3. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gc3d5,Re2e4][%csl Be4,Bd5]} { The battle for the center goes on. } ( { With } 3.Nf3 { starts the Anti-Nimzo-Indian that goes beyond the scope of this repertoire. } ) Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} { Here we are. By pinning the c3-knight, we enter into the subtle intricacies of the Nimzo-Indian Defense, named after the influential author of My System, Aron Nimzowitsch [https://www.chess.com/article/view/the-father-of-modern-chess] (1886-1935).

The statistics below come from a major online platform. We focus on rated games (Blitz to Classical) between players whose strength is from 1000 to 2000.

~ White can play: ~  (Use these percentages to optimize your learning, by training certain variations more than others.)

}
4.-- ( { ⭐ } 4.e3 { The Rubinstein System } ) { freq: 12%/img/diagrams/66044-1719954419.png Named after the 'uncrowned king' Akiba Rubinstein [https://www.chess.com/blog/kahns/a-century-of-chess-akiba-rubinstein-1900-1909-2] (1880-1961).

} ( { ⭐ } 4.Qc2 { The Classical Variation } ) { freq: 18%/img/diagrams/66044-1719999595.png Other name: 'Capablanca Variation'.

} { ⭐4.f3 The Kmoch Variation } { freq: 3%/img/diagrams/66044-1719999886.png Bearing the name of Hans Kmoch (1894-1973) , author of the classic Pawn Power in Chess. This line is also known as: 'Gheorghiu Variation' or 'Shirov Variation'.

} ( { ⭐ } 4.a3 { The Sämisch Variation } ) { freq: 11%/img/diagrams/66044-1720033590.png Named after Friedrich Sämisch (1896-1975) , the unfortunate opponent of Nimzowitsch during the 'Immortal Zugzwang Game'.

} ( { ⭐ } 4.Bg5 { The Leningrad Variation } ) { freq: 15%/img/diagrams/66044-1720033879.png So named because its theory was developed by Soviet players, including the 10th World Champion Boris Spassky, in what is now the city of St. Petersburg.

} ( { ⭐ } 4.Nf3 { The Three Knights Variation } ) { freq: 17%/img/diagrams/66044-1720034624.png Other name: 'Kasparov Variation' as the Beast of Baku played successfully (3 wins, 3 draws) 4.Nf3 against Anatoly Karpov in their 1985 World Championship match.

} ( { ⭐ } 4.g3 { The Romanishin Variation } ) { freq: 1%/img/diagrams/66044-1720035144.png It is so called because the Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin (b. 1952) has brought it up to date in the 1970s. Alternative name: 'Fianchetto Variation'

} ( { ⭐ } 4.Bd2 { what we call 'The Passive 4.Bd2' }  { freq: 17%/img/diagrams/66044-1720034874.png } )
