1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} ( { Black usually plays } 1...d5 { or the text move to prevent White from building a center with 2.e4. } ) 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} { Black defends the center and allows his Bishop on f8 to move as well. } 
3. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} { White develops his Knight and, at the same time, prepares to play 4.e4 with a big center. } Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Ye1,Yc3]} { This pins the Knight and prevents 4.e4, since, in that case, Black could just capture the pawn. This is the starting position of our course, The Nimzo-Indian. Each chapter will start in this position, and, in each chapter, we will look at different possible moves for White on move 4. } 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein System. 4.e3 is a normal move in the opening, since White wants to develop their King’s bishop (usually to d3) and sometimes put the g1-knight to e2. The drawback, if there is one, is that White cannot develop their c1-bishop actively to f4 or g5 soon. Sometimes, White plays e3-e4 later, and the bishop gets out anyway. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { Black has many choices here, but when I was younger (👦🏻much younger!) I used to play this with the black pieces. Black wants to develop his Bishop and with pawns on d7 and e6, it makes sense to develop the Bishop to b7 or a6. } 
5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2c3]} { White wants to recapture with the knight on c3 and not double his pawns. But now, the knight on e2 blocks the white bishop on f1. } ( { If } 5.Nf3 { then we play } 5...Bb7 6.Bd3 { and this transposes to the 5.Bd3-line. } ) Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Black can also play } 5...Ba6 { . But Kramnik and Karpov have won with } ) ( 5...Bb7 { : who am I to argue? } ) 
6. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} Be7 { Black decides to retreat the bishop. (Even if 6…Bxc3 is good too.)
Why?
🔹we claim that the white knight on e2 is misplaced by continuing to block the bishop on f1;
🔹keeping our bishop pair is a good idea when 6...Bxc3 doesn't double the pawns. } ( { ➢ In other words, with the white king’s knight on e2, 6…Be7 makes more sense since White is ready to recapture with this knight } 6...Bxc3 7.Nxc3 { , clearing the way for the bishop. } ) 
7. d5! { The only way to fight for an advantage. If Black is allowed to play d7-d5 then they have equalized and have easy play. } O-O 
8. e4 Re8! { Black plays ...Re8 with the idea of ...Bf8. We'll see it a few times in this repertoire. } 
9. g3 ( 9.Ng3 Bf8 { Transposes to the 8.Ng3-line [/variation/41417270]. } ) b5! {[%cal Gb5c4,Ge6d5,Gf6e4,Gb7e4,Be8e1]} { Putting maximum pressure on White's center before they are able to castle. } 
10. cxb5 Nxe4!! {[%cal Ge4c3]} 
11. Bg2 ( 11.Nxe4?! exd5! { leads to a discovered attack: see [/variation/41417272] the variation. } ) Nxc3 
12. Nxc3 exd5 {[%cal Ge8e1]} { White must avoid the discovered check on the e-file. } 
13. O-O c6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ge7f6]} { Black is a pawn ahead and White has sufficient compensation. The engine slightly prefers White, but a pawn is a pawn! } 
