1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { The Classical or Capablanca variation. This move is very common. White defends the knight on c3 and keeps a watch on the critical e4-square. } b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7a6][%csl Ba6,Bb7]} { Most of the lines in this course will focus on Black playing an early b7-b6. This allows the bishop on c8 to go to b7 (most likely) or even the a6-square. This move is not very popular, so, it will be less likely your opponent will be well-prepared. } 
5. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { Immediately putting the question to the bishop. In the Nimzo, Black usually plays Bxc3 when White plays a2-a3. } Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} 
6. Qxc3 { The point of 4.Qc2 is to recapture on the c3-square with the queen. } Bb7 { Black fianchettos their bishop, which is the main point of 4...b6. } 
7. Nf3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb7e4,Ge4c3][%csl Be4]} { Black dominates the e4-square at the moment, so puts his knight on this excellent post. } 
8. Qc2 O-O 
9. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3]} f5 {[%cal Gf5e4][%csl Be4]} { Black secures the knight on e4. I have had these kind of positions often as a teenager, and often I would win with a direct kingside attack. } 
10. Bd3 Rf6! { Black starts the kingside onslaught immediately! Black wants to play rook to g6 and attack! } ( { Q.: Why don't we play } 10...d6 { ?
A.: 10...d6 is fine as well. As long as we play ...Rf6 at some point. } ) 
11. O-O Rg6 {[%cal Gg6g2,Gb7g2][%csl Yf3,Yg2]} { Black has a good attack against the white king. Black's bishop on b7 and rook on g6 make for a nice attack against the g2-square. Some players prefer Bishop to e2 instead of bishop to d3 since the knight on f3 is defended a little more. }
12.-- ( { A. If White dares } 12.Ne5?! { , played quite frequently online, the answer is radical } 12...Rxg2+! 13.Kxg2 Qg5+ { . And Black’s attack is tremendous: } { 𓈓a1. 14.Kh1?? Nxf2# }{ 𓈓a2. 14.Kh3 d6! 15.Qe2 ( 15.Nf3?? Qg4# ) 𓈓15...dxe5 , and Black's attacking possibilities are worth more than the small material investment. }) ( { B. If } 12.d5! { White advances in the center to meet Black’s kingside attack } 12...exd5 13.Nd4 { , White wants to attack the f5-pawn and prepare to kick out the knight with f2-f3 } 13...Nc6 { Black develops their last minor piece } 14.f3 Nxd4 15.exd4 Qf6! { A very hard move to find, unless you buy the Chessable course! } 16.fxe4? dxe4 { , Black crashes through in the center and kingside } 17.Be2 Qxd4+ 18.Kh1 e3! 19.Bf3 Bxf3 { . Black is completely winning here and will soon play …Re8 and …f4. White has a difficult time with their king and with developing the queenside pieces, which are stuck. } )
