1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { The Classical or Capablanca variation. This move is very common. White defends the knight on c3 and keeps a watch on the critical e4-square. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7a6][%csl Ba6,Bb7]} { Most of the lines in this course will focus on Black playing an early b7-b6. This allows the bishop on c8 to go to b7 (most likely) or even the a6-square. This move is not very popular, so, it will be less likely your opponent will be well-prepared. } 
5. e4! {[%cal Gc4b5,Gc4d5,Gd4c5,Gd4e5,Ge4d5,Ge4f5][%csl Bf5,Be5,Bd5,Bc5,Bb5]} { This is the best move for White. White wants a big center. } c5! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc5d4]} { Immediately attacking the center. } 
6. d5 { This is the best try for an advantage. } Qe7! {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge7e1][%csl Yc3,Ye4]} { Firouzja and Tari both like this move. } 
7. Nge2! {[%cal Ge7e1][%csl Ge2]} { The only try for an advantage. White develops their knight and unpins the e4-pawn. } ( { If } 7.Be2 d6 8.Nf3 { , both sides develop quickly } 8...Bxc3+ 9.Qxc3 O-O 10.Bg5 Nbd7 { is equal, according to the engine. Black will soon play …h6 and try to break the pin and put pressure on the e4-pawn. } ) exd5 
8. exd5 ( 8.cxd5?! { loses a pawn to... } 8...Qxe4! ) O-O 
9. Bd2 d6 
10. O-O-O Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f2,Gf2h1,Gf2d1][%csl Yf2]} { The alternative move for White, instead of 10. O-O-O is 10.f3: /img/diagrams/66044-1719581972.png This prophylactic move is also discussed here [/variation/41429507] and avoids these lines with 10...Ng4. } 
11. Be1! {[%cal Ge1f2]} { White needed to defend the f2-pawn. } Qg5+ {[%csl Rc1]} 
12. Qd2 ( 12.f4? Qh6 { is great for Black, since White gave away the e3-square. } ) Qxd2+ {[%csl Rc1]} 
13. Kxd2 Nd7 { This double-edged position has chances for both sides, and reminds me of the Benoni pawn structure. In practice, Black scores over 50%. Black has excellent squares for their knights (f6 and e5) and will likely gain control over the only open file with a later ...Re8. } 
