1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. f3 c5 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc5d4]} ( { One of the few chapters where we don't play } 4...b6 { . White has insisted on playing e2-e4 very soon, so it's best to attack the d4-pawn. @@StartBlockQuote@@It's best to attack the white center before they can develop and castle. @@EndBlockQuote@@ In the chapter The Kmoch Variation 4.f3 in particular, we will often see that Black attacks the weak white c4-pawn with the queenside pieces. } ) 
5. d5 d6 ( 5...b5 { and } ) ( 5...O-O { are both fine as well. I think } ) ( 5...d6 { is easier to understand. Black wants to play ...Nbd7 soon. } ) 
6. e4 { The point of 4.f3 is to build a big center. In almost every line in the chapter on the Kmoch Variation [/course/258506/15], White plays e2-e4. } O-O 
7. Bd3 { White wants to develop their bishop before playing Nge2, and also keeps the c4-pawn protected in case Black plays some knight to e5 or ...b7-b5 soon. } b5! { This move is typical in this variation. Black tries to seize the initiative since White is uncastled. } 
8. Nge2 bxc4 { Black chomps away at White's center. } 
9. Bxc4 exd5 { Eliminating the big center. At the risk of repeating myself: @@StartBlockQuote@@Opening the center is a good idea when we've castled and our opponent has not.@@EndBlockQuote@@ } 
10. Bxd5 ( 10.exd5?! { This blocks the bishop on c4 and the half-open d-file that White had. } 10...Nbd7 11.O-O Ne5 { Black has a clear advantage. The pawn on f3 makes no sense now, and Black has ...Ba6 and ...Rb8 with excellent play. } ) Nxd5 
11. Qxd5 Be6! {[%cal Ge6d5]} 
12. Qxa8 Qb6! { The white queen is trapped. } 
13. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gf8a8,Gb6c6,Gb6b7,Gb6a7,Gg8f8][%csl Bb7,Bc6,Ba7,Bf8]} 
14. Qxf8+ Kxf8 {[%cal Gb6a6,Ga6e2,Be6c4,Gc6e5,Ge5c4,Ge5d3][%csl Bd3,Bc4]} { Black's pieces are all excellent and the engine prefers Black. We can play ...Ne5 and ...Qa6 putting pressure on the weak white squares. } 
