[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41576906"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} { The Leningrad Variation. An old favorite of Boris Spassky, although other World Champions and Super-GMs do not play it regularly. } b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc8b7]} { This is not very popular, but it scores well in practice. @@StartBlockQuote@@In this course, we try to play an early ...b6 whenever possible. @@EndBlockQuote@@ } ( { Most of your opponents will instead be prepared for } 4...h6 { or } ) ( 4...c5 { . } ) 
5. e3 Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} { Black destroys White's queenside pawn structure before White plays Nge2 defending the knight on c3. } 
6. bxc3 h6 {[%cal Gh6g5]} { Almost every variation of this chapter sees Black play h7-h6. } { 7...Bb7 makes little difference with our question to the White bishop on g5: nothing is forced, Black can play any move order and have a fine game. } 
7. Bh4 { White would always prefer to keep the two bishops. } ( 7.Bxf6?! Qxf6 { White has no development and a worse pawn structure. Black has nothing to fear. } ) Bb7 
8. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} { This is the only way for White to try to build a big center. Otherwise, Black should be slightly better. The only way for White to fight for an advantage is to get in e3-e4. Unfortunately for White, this means e2-e3 earlier just loses a tempo. } ( 8.Nf3 { , the move you're most likely to encounter, transposes into positions very similar to those of the Leningrad: 5.Nf3 lines #1 [/variation/41441014] & #2 [/variation/41441016]. } ) d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5,Gc7c5]} { This is the most flexible move. Black will likely play Nbd7 soon, and either e6-e5, c7-c5, or, in some cases, both! } 
9. Bd3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f6][%csl Yf6]} 
10. Ne2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gg7g5,Gf7f5,Ge6e5,Gc7c5,Ge8c8][%csl Yc3,Yc4,Ya2]} { Black can castle on either wing. This position is equal, but not drawish.

Black can soon play g7-g5, Nf6-h5, f7-f5, and O-O-O. Black is very flexible, and can play either e6-e5 or c7-c5 later. } 
