1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} { The Leningrad Variation. An old favorite of Boris Spassky, although other World Champions and Super-GMs do not play it regularly. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { This is not very popular, but it scores well in practice. @@StartBlockQuote@@In this course, we try to play an early ...b6 whenever possible. @@EndBlockQuote@@ } ( { Most of your opponents will instead be prepared for } 4...h6 { or } ) ( 4...c5 { . } ) 
5. Nf3 { This is the most common move. This can also come from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 b6 5.Bg5 . } h6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gh6g5]} { The favorite move of Anand and Carlsen, and many other Super-GMs. As I have written earlier, it's almost always correct to play h7-h6 in the chapter on the Leningrad Variation 4.Bg5 [/course/258506/17], to gain a tempo on the bishop on g5. } 
6. Bh4 ( 6.Bxf6?! Bxc3+ ! 7.bxc3 Qxf6 { Black has nothing to fear when White plays Bxf6 in this chapter. Now, Black just has a better pawn structure, and White does not have the two bishops as compensation. } ) g5! {[%cal Gg5h4]} { All Super-GMs play this way. } 
7. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb4e1,Ge4c3,Gf7f4,Ge4g3,Gf7f5][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} { Black seizes the initiative! } 
8. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { Defends the White knight on c3. } Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4]} 
9. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3]} Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} 
10. bxc3 d6 {[%cal Gb8d7]} { This allows Black to play Nd7 soon, and Black can later play Nxg3 at their leisure. } 
11. Bd3 {[%cal Rc2e4]} f5! {[%cal Gf5e4]} { Fighting for the e4-square is key in many Nimzo lines. There is no reason to take on g3 so quickly when Black can bolster the knight on e4. } 
12. d5 {[%cal Bd6c5,Bb6c5,Rd5e6]} { This is the only way to fight for the center, but it doesn't really cause Black any trouble, since it gives away the c5-square. } Na6! { Black hastens to play Nac5 and White's queenside pawns don't look very good. } 
13. Bxe4 { White snatches a pawn, but the resulting pawn structure means Black is at least equal. } ( 13.Nd4 Nac5 { Black has everything they want here. } ) fxe4 {[%cal Ge4f3]} 
14. Qxe4 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6c3,Gf6g6,Gf6e6][%csl Yc3,Bg6]} { This gives Black a slightly better endgame due to White's ruined pawn structure.

See the whole variation here [/variation/41441016]. } 
