[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Three Knights Variation 4.Nf3"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E21"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41592022"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Nf3 { This is likely to transpose to other chapters. We will look at other lines that can't happen elsewhere in the course. } b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc8b7]} { As per usual. } 
5. Qb3 {[%cal Rb3b4]} ( 5.Bg5 { is the most played move in this position. It transposes to our Leningrad: 5.Nf3 [https://www.chessable.com/course/258506/fen/rnbqk2r;p1pp1ppp;1p2pn2;6B1;1bPP4;2N2N2;PP2PPPP;R2QKB1R%20b%20KQkq%20-%201%205/] lines. } ) c5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gc5b4][%csl Bd4]} { Attacking the d4-pawn when the White queen moves off of its defense is a common idea in the Nimzo. } 
6. dxc5 Bxc5 {[%cal Gc5b6,Gc5g1]} { This is the correct way to recapture. Now the queen on b3 isn't pressuring our potential bishop on b7. } 
7. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} Bb7 {[%cal Gb7h1]} { Putting the bishop on the excellent long diagonal. } ( { Any move order should just transpose, such as } 7...h6 8.Bh4 Bb7 { . It is the same! } ) 
8. e3 h6 {[%cal Gh6g5]} { It's almost a given that we play ....h6 when the white bishop is on g5. } 
9. Bh4 Be7! {[%cal Ge7h4,Gb8a6,Ga6c5,Gc5b3][%csl Yb3]} { The bishop wasn't doing much on the c5-square, but here we unpin the knight on f6, and allow our queen's knight to get to the excellent c5-square. } 
10. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} O-O 
11. O-O Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gb7h1,Gf6e4,Gd7d5,Be7h4,Bh4e7][%csl Yb3]} { Black is completely equal. White's queen is misplaced on the b3-square, and we can play ...Nc5, either knight to e4, and ...d5. } 
