[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "1) Rubinstein System 4.e3"]
[Black "Rubinstein: 5.Bd3 with 8.a3 #1"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E43"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41417260"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} ( { Black usually plays } 1...d5 { or the text move to prevent White from building a center with 2.e4. } ) 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} { Black defends the center and allows his Bishop on f8 to move as well. } 
3. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} { White develops his Knight and, at the same time, prepares to play 4.e4 with a big center. } Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Ye1,Yc3]} { This pins the Knight and prevents 4.e4, since, in that case, Black could just capture the pawn. This is the starting position of our course, The Nimzo-Indian. Each chapter will start in this position, and, in each chapter, we will look at different possible moves for White on move 4. } 
4. e3 { The Rubinstein System. 4.e3 is a normal move in the opening, since White wants to develop their King’s bishop (usually to d3) and sometimes put the g1-knight to e2. The drawback, if there is one, is that White cannot develop their c1-bishop actively to f4 or g5 soon. Sometimes, White plays e3-e4 later, and the bishop gets out anyway. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { Black has many choices here, but when I was younger (👦🏻much younger!) I used to play this with the black pieces. Black wants to develop his Bishop and with pawns on d7 and e6, it makes sense to develop the Bishop to b7 or a6. } 
5. Bd3 { White develops their Bishop to an active square and prepares to develop the kingside and castle. } ( { If } 5.Nf3 { then we play } 5...Bb7 6.Bd3 { and this transposes to the 5.Bd3-line. } ) Bb7 {[%cal Gb7h1][%csl Yg2]} { Black fianchettos their bishop, the point of 4...b6. } 
6. Nf3 { White develops the knight and prepares to castle kingside. Also, this prevents Black from winning material with ...Bxg2. } O-O ( { When I was between 8 and 14 years old, I used to play } 6...Ne4 { which is more aggressive. But I believe this is a better way to get at least an equal game. Developing pieces and castling is what the course is all about! } ) 
7. O-O c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} ( { Black can also play } 7...d5 { , but the text move is the most popular now among the Super-GMs. Black puts pressure on White's center. } ) 
8. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { White decides to get the two bishops immediately. } Bxc3 
9. bxc3 { A typical Nimzo position. White has two bishops, but Black has a much better pawn structure, and the white bishop on c1 isn't very good. } Ne4! {[%cal Gb7e4][%csl Be4]} { One of the key goals of the Nimzo is to control and/or occupy the e4-square. Black is first! } 
10. Nd2 {[%cal Rd2e4]} f5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gb8d7,Gd8h4,Gf8f6,Gf6h6][%csl Be4,Yc1]} { Black defends the knight and gains space on the kingside. This, f5, is typical once Black plays knight to e4 in many lines. } ( { Black shouldn't be greedy with: } 10...Nxc3 11.Qc2 { . This traps the black knight. } ) ( { After } 10...f5 { , the engine says chances are about equal. But, it is more difficult to play with White, since the Bishop on c1 is so poor. Black will continue with ...d7-d6 and ...Nb8-d7 and have nice control of the center and a better pawn structure. Black also has good chances for a Kingside attack by moving his queen and rook into the vicinity of the white king. } )
11.-- ( { If 11.Nxe4 fxe4 12.Bc2 Qh4 , Black takes up an aggressive posture on the kingside. The e4-pawn is quite strong and basically kills both white bishops, as they struggle to get active. 13.a4 White wants to play 14.a5 and get rid of the isolated a-pawn 13...Rf6 . The engine slightly prefers Black due to a potential kingside attack and white’s passive bishops. Sometimes doubled pawns are strong, and here, the e4-pawn is quite annoying for White. } )
*

