4. e3 { The Rubinstein System. 4.e3 is a normal move in the opening, since White wants to develop their King’s bishop (usually to d3) and sometimes put the g1-knight to e2. The drawback, if there is one, is that White cannot develop their c1-bishop actively to f4 or g5 soon. Sometimes, White plays e3-e4 later, and the bishop gets out anyway. } b6 { Black has many choices here, but when I was younger (👦🏻much younger!) I used to play this with the black pieces. Black wants to develop his Bishop and with pawns on d7 and e6, it makes sense to develop the Bishop to b7 or a6. } 
5. Bd3 { White develops their Bishop to an active square and prepares to develop the kingside and castle. } ( { If } 5.Nf3 { then we play } 5...Bb7 6.Bd3 { and this transposes to the 5.Bd3-line. } ) Bb7 {[%cal Gb7h1]} { Black fianchettos their bishop, the point of 4...b6. } 
6. Nf3 { White develops the knight and prepares to castle kingside. Also, this prevents Black from winning material with ...Bxg2. } O-O ( { When I was between 8 and 14 years old, I used to play } 6...Ne4 { which is more aggressive. But I believe this is a better way to get at least an equal game. Developing pieces and castling is what the course is all about! } ) 
7. O-O c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} ( { Black can also play } 7...d5 { , but the text move is the most popular now among the Super-GMs. Black puts pressure on White's center. } ) 
8. Bd2 { This passive move doesn't give White any advantage. } cxd4 
9. exd4 d5 { Black gains space in the center. Once Black plays c7-c5 and d7-d5 they have a fine position. } 
10. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} Bxc3 {[%csl Be4]} { I chose that move because I like to control the e4-square. } ( { Black can also safely play } 10...dxc4 { or } ) ( 10...Be7 { with an equal game. They are good as well! @@StartBlockQuote@@That’s a great thing about the Nimzo for Black: it’s not necessary to memorize a lot of stuff, since, often, many moves are fine!@@EndBlockQuote@@ } ) 
11. Bxc3  dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc4d3]} 
12. Bxc4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8c4,Gf6d5,Ga8c8][%csl Yc4,Bc8,Bd5]} { The opening is over, and the engine prefers Black here. White has a blockaded bishop on c3 and an isolated pawn on d4. Black has nice development, a safe king, and will soon play ...Ra8-c8 and ...Nf6-d5 with great control of key squares. } 
