4. e3 { The Rubinstein System. 4.e3 is a normal move in the opening, since White wants to develop their King’s bishop (usually to d3) and sometimes put the g1-knight to e2. The drawback, if there is one, is that White cannot develop their c1-bishop actively to f4 or g5 soon. Sometimes, White plays e3-e4 later, and the bishop gets out anyway. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { Black has many choices here, but when I was younger (👦🏻much younger!) I used to play this with the black pieces. Black wants to develop his Bishop and with pawns on d7 and e6, it makes sense to develop the Bishop to b7 or a6. } 
5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2c3]} { White wants to recapture with the knight on c3 and not double his pawns. But now, the knight on e2 blocks the white bishop on f1. } ( { If } 5.Nf3 { then we play } 5...Bb7 6.Bd3 { and this transposes to the 5.Bd3-line. } ) Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Black can also play } 5...Ba6 { . But Kramnik and Karpov have won with } ) ( 5...Bb7 { : who am I to argue? } ) 
