9. Be2 { White develops and prepares to castle. } Bf8 { Always play Bf8! } 
10. e4 { White strengthens their center. } d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd6e5]} { Black prevents e4-e5 and will soon play ...Nbd7. } 
11. O-O Nbd7 
12. Be3 c6 { The engine prefers White, but Black has scored well in this position in practice. One key game in this position occurred in the game Kasparov-Kramnik (2001), and Kramnik eventually won. Black has great pressure on White's center. } 
