1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { The Classical or Capablanca variation. This move is very common. White defends the knight on c3 and keeps a watch on the critical e4-square. } b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7a6][%csl Ba6,Bb7]} { Most of the lines in this course will focus on Black playing an early b7-b6. This allows the bishop on c8 to go to b7 (most likely) or even the a6-square. This move is not very popular, so, it will be less likely your opponent will be well-prepared. } 
5. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { Immediately putting the question to the bishop. In the Nimzo, Black usually plays Bxc3 when White plays a2-a3. } Bxc3+ 
6. Qxc3 { The point of 4.Qc2 is to recapture on the c3-square with the queen. } Bb7 { Black fianchettos their bishop, which is the main point of 4...b6. } 
7. Nf3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb7e4,Ge4c3][%csl Be4]} { Black dominates the e4-square at the moment, so puts his knight on this excellent post. } 
8. Qc2 O-O 
9. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} { White may prefer to fianchetto their bishop on the same diagonal as Black did previously. } f5 { A typical plan in the Nimzo for Black is to play knight to e4 and ....f7-f5 to secure the e4-square. } 
10. Bg2 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} { Kasparov has played this before, successfully, so, I figure it's good enough for this course! } 
11. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} { White defends the d4-square again and develops their last minor piece. } Nc6 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gc6d4,Gb7h1][%csl Be4,Bf5,Yd4]} { This position is about equal. Both sides have completed development (as long as White castles soon) and have a big fight for the central squares. Black has pressure on the d4-square and occupies the e4-square, both of which are great in the Nimzo lines. } 
