4. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { The Classical or Capablanca variation. This move is very common. White defends the knight on c3 and keeps a watch on the critical e4-square. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7a6][%csl Ba6,Bb7]} { Most of the lines in this course will focus on Black playing an early b7-b6. This allows the bishop on c8 to go to b7 (most likely) or even the a6-square. This move is not very popular, so, it will be less likely your opponent will be well-prepared. } 
5. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { Immediately putting the question to the bishop. In the Nimzo, Black usually plays Bxc3 when White plays a2-a3. } Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} 
6. Qxc3 { The point of 4.Qc2 is to recapture on the c3-square with the queen. } Bb7 { Black fianchettos their bishop, which is the main point of 4...b6. } 
7. f3 { This prevents Black from occupying the e4-square with their knight, and prepares for White to play e2-e4 soon. } d5! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Ye1,Yf1,Yg1,Yh1]} { This excellent response stops White in their tracks, as far as e2-e4 is concerned. Now White needs to figure out a way to develop their kingside. } { 7…c5 is also fine. I prefer 7…d5, but both are equally good. } 
8. Bg5 O-O { Black castles way before White, and is ready to complete development and attack the center with 9...Nbd7 and 10...c5. } 
