6. bxc3 Nc6 { Black has a lead in development, which often happens when White only makes pawn moves. } 
7. e4 d6 { Since Black has traded their dark-squared bishop, putting the center pawns on dark squares is logical. Black will likely try to play ...e5 at some point. } 
8. Ne2 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} { Black wants to get the bishop on c8 to a better place, usually the a6-square. } 
9. Ng3 ( 9.Bg5 h6 { A good 📌rule of thumb in the Nimzo is to play ...h6 when White plays Bg5. } 10.Bh4 O-O { The engine already prefers Black. Black can lock up the center with ...e5 and play against the weak c4-pawn with ...Na5, ...Ba6, and ...Rc8. } ) Na5! { Immediately putting pressure on the c4-pawn. } 
10. Bd3 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6c4,Ga5c4,Ge8g8][%csl Yc4]} { Black is slightly better. Black's play is clearly going to be against the c4-pawn. Black will castle and try to win the pawn ASAP. } 
