3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. f3 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4]} ( { One of the few chapters where we don't play } 4...b6 { . White has insisted on playing e2-e4 very soon, so it's best to attack the d4-pawn. @@StartBlockQuote@@It's best to attack the white center before they can develop and castle. @@EndBlockQuote@@ In this chapter, in particular, we will often see that Black attacks the weak white c4-pawn with the queenside pieces. } ) 
5. d5 d6 ( 5...b5 { and } ) ( 5...O-O { are both fine as well. I think } ) ( 5...d6 { is easier to understand. Black wants to play ...Nbd7 soon. } ) 
6. e4 { The point of 4.f3 is to build a big center. In almost every variation in this chapter, White plays e2-e4. } O-O 
7. Nge2 b5! {[%mdl 32768]} { This is typical in this chapter to attack White's pawn chain in the center. Black has already castled and is ready for aggressive operations, whereas White needs to develop and castle still. } 
8. Ng3 { The idea of this is to unblock the bishop on f1, so White defends the c4-pawn and can soon develop the bishop and castle. } Re8 {[%cal Ge8e1]} { This has been played by Pragg and Sevian. It's almost always a good idea to put the rook on the same file as the white king. } 
9. Bf4 exd5 { The idea is to make White recapture with the c4-pawn, so we can play ...c4 ourselves! } 
10. cxd5 c4 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7c5][%csl Bc5]} { This allows our queen's knight to get to the c5-square later. } 
11. a4 {[%cal Ra4b5]} { Trying to break up Black's nice pawns on the queenside. } bxa4 {[%csl Yc4,Ya4]} 
12. Rxa4 {[%cal Ra4b4][%csl Yb4]} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4]} { Defending our nice bishop on b4. } 
13. Bxc4 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5,Gd8b6,Gc8a6][%csl Yb2,Ya4]} { Black has full compensation for the sacrificed pawn. Black has good access to the c5- or e5-squares for their knights and Black can later play ...Qb6 to activate the queen.
It is reasonable to trade the LSB since our bishop on c8 is very passive and by trading, we get to use the c4 or d3 squares for our knight on d7. } 
