[ECO "E24"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41440836"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { The Sämisch Variation. White forces matters immediately. White loses a tempo with this move and ruins their queenside pawn structure. In compensation, White gets the two bishops and attempts to build a big center. } Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} 
5. bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { We try to play ...b7-b6 early whenever possible in the Nimzo! } 
6. e3 Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. Ne2!? {[%cal Ge2g3]} { This doesn't work out very well. } ( 7.Nf3 { Transposes to the 6.Nf3 with 7.e3 line [/variation/5444538]. } ) d6 
8. Ng3 h5! {[%cal Gh5h4]} { One idea I learned a long time ago, is to often play ...h7-h5 when my opponent has a knight on the g3-square. } 
9. h4 Qe7 
10. a4 {[%cal Ra4a5]} { White wants to trade their isolated a-pawn, but Black can develop and prevent White from achieving this! } Nc6! 
11. e4 {[%cal Rc1g5]} Nd7! { This prophylactic move stops the potential Bg5 pin. That pin is quite strong, since black can never play …h7-h6. } 
12. Nxh5?! {[%cal Gd1h5]} { The trade of h-pawns helps Black since they can safely castle queenside. } g6 {[%cal Gg6h5]} 
13. Ng3 ( 13.Bg5? f6! ) Rxh4 {[%cal Gf6h4,Ge7h4]} 
14. Rxh4 Qxh4 {[%cal Ge8c8][%csl Ye1]} { The engine (and your author!) likes Black. White's king really has nowhere safe to go. } 
