[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "4) Sämisch Variation 4.a3"]
[Black "Sämisch: 6.Nf3 with 7.e3"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E24"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41440839"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { The Sämisch Variation. White forces matters immediately. White loses a tempo with this move and ruins their queenside pawn structure. In compensation, White gets the two bishops and attempts to build a big center. } Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} 
5. bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { We try to play ...b7-b6 early whenever possible in the Nimzo! } 
6. Nf3 { White makes a simple developing move. This doesn't go well with 4.a3, since White could have played 4.Nf3 immediately (See the chapter on the Three Knights Variation [/course/258506/4]). } Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 
7. e3 O-O { White isn't building a big center, so Black can play simple moves and get a good game. } 
8. Bd3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb7e4][%csl Be4]} { The e4-square is key in the Nimzo. This prevents White from playing e3-e4 and keeps the bishop on the c1-square from developing. } 
9. Qc2 {[%cal Rc2e4]} f5! {[%cal Gf5e4]} { I had a lot of these kinds of positions in my teens and usually got a winning attack against White's king. } 
10. O-O d6 
11. Nd2 ( 11.Ne1 { This prevents Black from trading knights, but the knight isn't very good on the e1-square. } 11...Nd7 12.f3 Ng5 { This position is difficult to play for White. The bishop on the c1-square isn't very good and White has weak queenside pawns. Black can attack on the kingside with a rook lift or a queen lift (!) and has active pieces and a better pawn structure. The engine prefers Black. } ) Nxd2 
12. Bxd2 Nc6 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gf8f6,Gf6g6,Gb7g2][%csl Ya3,Bb7,Yc3,Yc4,Yd2,Yd3]} { White's bishops don't do much, so Black is better with their much better pawn structure and solid position. If you like to attack, you can do the usual queen and rook lifts toward White's king. } 
*

