1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} { The Leningrad Variation. An old favorite of Boris Spassky, although other World Champions and Super-GMs do not play it regularly. } b6 { This is not very popular, but it scores well in practice. @@StartBlockQuote@@In this course, we try to play an early ...b6 whenever possible. @@EndBlockQuote@@ } ( { Most of your opponents will instead be prepared for } 4...h6 { or } ) ( 4...c5 { . } ) 
5. f3 { White wants to build the big center, but, this does not go well with 4.Bg5. If White wants to play f2-f3 and e2-e4 then he do so on move 4, which is another chapter [/course/258506/5]. } h6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gh6g5]} 
6. Bh4 { White prefers to keep their bishop is at all possible. } c5! {[%cal Gc5d4]} { Attacking the White center before White gets going with e2-e4. } 
7. d5 ( 7.a3?! Bxc3+ 8.bxc3 Nc6 9.e4 d6 { White is mixing three variations (f3, Bg5, a3) and has no development on the kingside as a consequence. Black is already better and will continue with ...O-O, ...Ba6, and ...Rc8 to pressure the weak c4-pawn. } ) O-O 
8. e4 { White gets their center, but the kingside development is clearly in Black's favor. } Re8! {[%cal Ge8e1,Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1,Ye4]} { This makes things difficult for White. The White king needs protection! } ( 8...Bxc3+ { is also good for Black. With the knight on e2, White has trouble developing the bishop on f1 and castling. So both are fine for Black. } ) 
9. Nge2! {[%csl Ge2]} { This defensive move is best. } ( 9.e5? Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 exd5! { This pins the e5-pawn and White's position is already losing. } ) exd5 
10. cxd5 d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8a6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5][%csl Ye1,Yf1,Yh1]} { Hans Niemann has had White in this position four times and only has one draw to show for his efforts! This looks like a weird Benoni where White will have trouble untangling their kingside pieces and castling. Black has many plans, such as ...a6 and ...b5 or ...Ba6 to pressure White's position. } 
