3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} { The Leningrad Variation. An old favorite of Boris Spassky, although other World Champions and Super-GMs do not play it regularly. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { This is not very popular, but it scores well in practice. @@StartBlockQuote@@In this course, we try to play an early ...b6 whenever possible. @@EndBlockQuote@@ } ( { Most of your opponents will instead be prepared for } 4...h6 { or } ) ( 4...c5 { . } ) 
5. Nf3 { This is the most common move. This can also come from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 b6 5.Bg5 . } h6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gh6g5]} { The favorite move of Anand and Carlsen, and many other Super-GMs. As I have written earlier, it's almost always correct to play h7-h6 in this chapter, to gain a tempo on the bishop on g5. } 
6. Bh4 ( 6.Bxf6?! Bxc3+ ! 7.bxc3 Qxf6 { Black has nothing to fear when White plays Bxf6 in this chapter. Now, Black just has a better pawn structure, and White does not have the two bishops as compensation. } ) g5! {[%cal Gg5h4]} { All Super-GMs play this way. } 
7. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb4e1,Ge4c3,Gf7f4,Ge4g3,Gf7f5][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} { Black seizes the initiative! } 
8. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Rc2e4]} { Defends the White knight on c3. } Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4]} 
9. Nd2 {[%cal Rd2e4,Rc2e4,Gb7e4,Rc3e4]} { Attacking the black knight. This isn't tough for Black, since they can ruin White's pawn structure on both wings. } Bxc3 { Once again giving White weak pawns on the queenside. } 
10. bxc3 Nxg3 
11. hxg3 {[%cal Gb7h1][%csl Yc3,Yc4,Yg2,Yg3]} { White has two sets of doubled pawns, and Black has a nice bishop on b7. } d6 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 
12. e4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ge8c8][%csl Yc3,Yc4,Yg2,Yg3]} { The opening is over and the engine slightly prefers Black. Black also scores well at the GM level. White has a nice center, but Black has a much better pawn structure.

Black can safely castle on the queenside, whereas White's king is unsafe anywhere it goes. For example, if White castles kingside, Black can advance on that wing with h6-h5-h4 with a strong attack. } 
*

[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "5) Leningrad Variation 4.Bg5"]
[Black "Leningrad: 5.Nf3 #2"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E30"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/41441016"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Yf6,Yd8]} { The Leningrad Variation. An old favorite of Boris Spassky, although other World Champions and Super-GMs do not play it regularly. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { This is not very popular, but it scores well in practice. @@StartBlockQuote@@In this course, we try to play an early ...b6 whenever possible. @@EndBlockQuote@@ } ( { Most of your opponents will instead be prepared for } 4...h6 { or } ) ( 4...c5 { . } ) 
5. Nf3 { This is the most common move. This can also come from the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nf3 b6 5.Bg5 . } h6 {[%cal Gh6g5]} { The favorite move of Anand and Carlsen, and many other Super-GMs. As I have written earlier, it's almost always correct to play h7-h6 in this chapter, to gain a tempo on the bishop on g5. } 
6. Bh4 ( 6.Bxf6?! Bxc3+ ! 7.bxc3 Qxf6 { Black has nothing to fear when White plays Bxf6 in this chapter. Now, Black just has a better pawn structure, and White does not have the two bishops as compensation. } ) g5! {[%cal Gg5h4]} { All Super-GMs play this way. } 
7. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Gb4e1,Ge4c3,Gf7f4,Ge4g3,Gf7f5][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} { Black seizes the initiative! } 
8. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3]} { Defends the White knight on c3. } Bb7 {[%cal Gb7e4]} 
9. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3]} Bxc3+ {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Re1]} 
10. bxc3 d6 {[%cal Gb8d7]} { This allows Black to play Nd7 soon, and Black can later play Nxg3 at their leisure. } 
11. Bd3 {[%cal Rc2e4]} f5! {[%cal Gf5e4]} { Fighting for the e4-square is key in many Nimzo lines. There is no reason to take on g3 so quickly when Black can bolster the knight on e4. } 
12. d5 {[%cal Bd6c5,Bb6c5,Rd5e6]} { This is the only way to fight for the center, but it doesn't really cause Black any trouble, since it gives away the c5-square. } Na6! { Black hastens to play Nac5 and White's queenside pawns don't look very good. } 
13. Bxe4 { White snatches a pawn, but the resulting pawn structure means Black is at least equal. } ( 13.Nd4 Nac5 { Black has everything they want here. } ) fxe4 {[%cal Ge4f3]} 
14. Qxe4 {[%cal Re4e6,Re4g6]} Qf6! {[%cal Gf6e6,Gf6g6,Gf6c3][%csl Yc3]} { This gives Black a slightly better endgame due to White's ruined pawn structure. } 
15. Qxe6+ {[%csl Re8]} Qxe6 
16. dxe6 Nc5 {[%cal Gb7h1,Gc5e6,Gc5e4][%csl Ya2,Yc3,Yc4,Ye6,Yg3]} { The engine prefers Black here, and, in practice, Black scores well. } 
