[Event "Starting Out: Nimzo-Indian Defense"]
[White "6) Three Knights Variation 4.Nf3"]
[Black "Three Knights: 5.Bd2 with 6.e3"]
[Date "2024.10.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E21"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/43116377"]

1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Nf3 { This is likely to transpose to other chapters. We will look at other lines that can't happen elsewhere in the course. } b6 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gc8b7]} { As per usual. } 
5. Bd2 { This move transposes to one of our Passive 4.Bd2 [/variation/43151143] lines. It used to be only weak players would play Bc1-d2 in any variation of the Nimzo. Nowadays, top players play Bc1-d2 in many variations! Luckily, this should give White no advantage. } ( 5.Bg5 { is the most played move in this position. It transposes to our Leningrad: 5.Nf3 [https://www.chessable.com/course/258506/fen/rnbqk2r;p1pp1ppp;1p2pn2;6B1;1bPP4;2N2N2;PP2PPPP;R2QKB1R%20b%20KQkq%20-%201%205/] lines. } ) Bb7 {[%csl Bb7,Bb4]} { The usual piece placement in the course. } 
6. e3 {[%cal Gd7d5]} { Playing 5.Nd2 and 6.e3 is too passive to give White chances for an advantage. } O-O 
7. Bd3 d5 ( 7...c5 { is also good. Black has more than one way to get an equal game, since 5.Bd2 is so passive. } ) 
8. cxd5 exd5 
9. O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e8,Gc7c5]} { The bishop no longer wants to trade for the white knight and can simply go to the nice d6-square, since White can never play e4-e5 like in other Nimzo variations. The position is equal, and Black can simply play ...Nbd7, ...Re8 and ...c7-c5 with a fine position. } 
*

