1. d4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Re2e4][%csl Be4]} 
2. c4 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8b4][%csl Bd5]} 
3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} { White wants to fianchetto quickly. This reminds me of the Catalan Opening, although this seems like a good version for Black. } O-O ( { We shouldn't play our usual } 4...b6 { , since White plays } 5.Bg2 { , so we castle! @@StartBlockQuote@@One of the biggest advantages Black has in the Nimzo is that we almost always castle way before White does.@@EndBlockQuote@@ } ) 
5. Bg2 d5 {[%cal Gd5c4]} { Black has many good moves, but this is the best. We fight for the center. } 
6. Nf3 dxc4 { Black wants to make White work to regain the pawn, and, in some variations, black is simply a pawn ahead } 
7. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Ga5b3][%csl Gc4]} { Black develops quickly. Often black wants to play ...Na5 defending their pawn. } 
8. a3 {[%cal Ra3b4]} { Putting the question to the bishop. } Be7! {[%mdl 32768]} { There is no reason to trade the bishop, and Black can look forward to being ahead a pawn without giving up the two bishops. } 
9. e4 { If White had played e4 earlier, then Black would play ...Bxc3 and ...Nxe4. Now, White can grab the center. } Na5 { White has the center, but Black has an extra pawn! } 
10. Be3 c6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga5b3]} { White has compensation for the pawn, but I prefer Black. We can later play ...b5 and ...Nb3 and have a nice bind on the queenside. } 
