3. Nc3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Yc3,Ye1]} 
4. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} { Played frequently at the club level, but make only sporadic appearances at the top one. This is pretty passive and doesn't fight for an advantage. } b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} { Sticking with our 4...b6 policy! } 
5. Nf3 Bb7 
6. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3]} ( 6.a3 { (Bd2 and a3 ideas by White are always too slow to hope for an advantage) } 6...Bxc3 7.Bxc3 Ne4 8.Rc1 { . This transposes to the 4.Bd2 with 5.a3 variation (e.g. see: #1 [/variation/41443391] & #2 [/variation/41443392]). } ) O-O {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Bb4e1,Bb7f3,Bf6e4][%csl Bb7,Bb4,Bf6]} { Black castles and has excellent pieces. } 
7. Bd3 d5 { This is the best move. White hasn't done anything aggressive, so we can just play in the center. } ( 7...c5 { is also good. } ) 
8. cxd5 exd5 
9. O-O {[%cal Gb4d6][%csl Yd2]} Bd6 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8d7,Gf8e8]} { The bishop no longer wants to trade for the white knight and can simply go to the nice d6-square, since White can never play e4-e5 like in other Nimzo variations. The position is equal, and Black can simply play ...Nbd7, ...Re8 and ...c7-c5 with a fine position. } 
