11. O-O Nc6 {[%csl Yd4]} { Black threatens to capture on d4. } 
12. d5!? ( { White plays the most aggressive move, but } 12.Be3 { should lead to an equal position with chances for both sides. } ) exd5 
13. cxd5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5,Gb7d5][%csl Yd5]} { Black has tremendous pressure on the d5-pawn. } 
14. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]} { This leads to trades which, more or less, lead to an equal position. } Bxd5 
15. Nxe4 Bxe4 {[%cal Yg2e4][%csl Rg2,Rc2]} 
16. Bxe4 fxe4 
17. Qxe4 d5 {[%csl Re4]} { This looks very equal, but, it's a blitz game, so either can side can play for a win. } 
18. Qe6+ Rf7 
19. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8][%csl Ye7]} Qc8! { Breaking the pin and attacking the white queen. } 
20. Qd6 Qb7 
21. Bxe7 Rxe7 { In a slow game, between players of equal strength, I would expect a draw to be the most likely outcome from here. } 
22. e3 Rae8 
23. Rad1 Rd7 {[%csl Rd6]} 
24. Qf4 h6 { Luft for the king. The best chance for Black to gain an advantage is to get a passed d-pawn. } 
25. Rd2 Qc6 
26. Rfd1 Qe6 
27. Qf3 Red8 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 
28. Qf4 { White doesn't have an active plan, so shuffles his queen. } a5 
29. Qa4 Rd6 {[%cal Gd6b6][%csl Gb6]} 
30. Qb5 d4 { Black goes for it! } 
31. exd4 Rxd4 
32. Rxd4 Rxd4 
33. Rxd4 cxd4 
34. Qd3 Qd5 { Today's engines would draw this effortlessly. But, this is an engine from long ago! } 
35. h4 a4 
36. f3 { @@StartBlockQuote@@Never play f3!@@EndBlockQuote@@ Although this is fine here. } b5 
37. Kf2 Kf7 
38. Ke2 h5 
39. Kd2 Qe5 
40. Qe4?? { Leads to a lost king and pawn endgame. Humans still had a chance in 1997! } ( 40.Kd1 Qxg3 41.Qf5+ Ke7 42.Qc5+ Kf7 43.Qf5+= ) Qxe4 
41. fxe4 Ke6 
42. Ke2 ( 42.Kd3 Ke5-+ ) Ke5 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gg7g6][%csl Re4]} 
