1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nf3 b6 
4. Nc3 Bb4 
5. Qb3 {[%csl Rb4]} { This is a transposition from the Three Knights chapter [/course/258506/18], the lines with 4.Nf3 b6 5.Qb3. } c5 {[%cal Gc5b4,Gc5d4][%csl Gb4,Rd4]} { When White plays Qb3 in the Nimzo, Black usually plays ...c5 in response to put pressure on the d4-pawn and defend the bishop on b4. } 
6. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6]} h6 {[%csl Rg5]} 
7. Bh4 g5! {[%csl Rh4]} { Black plays in the most aggressive way. } 
8. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Ge4g3,Ge4c3,Gc5d4][%csl Yd4,Rg3,Rc3]} { Black has pressure in White's position. } 
9. e3 Bb7 
10. Bd3 Bxc3+ {[%csl Re1]} { Black initiates trades to ruin White's pawn structure. } 
11. bxc3 Nxg3 
12. hxg3 Nc6 {[%csl Cc3,Cc4,Cg2,Cg3]} { White has two sets of doubled pawns. Black has at least equalized. } 
13. Qc2 Qe7 { Black prepares to castle queenside, which is common when we have played an early ...g5. } 
14. Qe2 O-O-O 
15. g4 Na5 {[%cal Gb7f3,Ga5c4][%csl Cc4,Cf3]} { Black puts pressure on White's position. Conversely, White has little pressure on Black's position. } 
16. e4 Qf6 
17. Qe3 d6 { White has a nice center, but where does he put his king? } 
18. Nd2 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc5d4,Gf6d4][%csl Yd4]} { The c4-pawn is well defended, so Black attacks the d4-pawn instead. } 
19. Nb3 e5! { This makes the white bishop rather dead. } 
20. d5 Ne7 
21. Nd2 Kc7 { Although I like Black here, the engine says White is still about equal, since it's so blocked in the center. Black clears the c8-square for their bishop. } 
22. Nf1 Bc8 
23. Be2 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4][%csl Bf4]} 
24. g3 {[%cal Bg3f4]} Ne7 
25. Bf3 Qg6 
26. Qe2 Ng8 {[%cal Gg8f6][%csl Ye4,Yg4]} 
27. Ne3 Nf6 
28. Qc2 Bd7 { Good piece placement by both sides. Now White castles very late in the game! } 
29. O-O-O?! Rh7 
30. Rh2 Rdh8 
31. Rdh1 { White tries to thwart Black at every turn. Usually, passive play like this doesn't work, and, Black soon breaks through. } Qg8 
32. Be2 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8g4,Gf6g4][%csl Rg4]} 
33. f3? { @@StartBlockQuote@@Never play f3!@@EndBlockQuote@@ } h5! 
34. gxh5 Rxh5 
35. Bd3 Qg8 
36. Rxh5 Nxh5 {[%cal Gh5g3][%csl Rg3]} 
37. Qg2 Nf6 
38. g4? { This loses. After a tough defense, White allows Black to come in on the kingside. } Rh4! 
39. Kd2 ( 39.Rxh4 gxh4 { is winning for Black. Black has a passed h-pawn and can infiltrate on the dark squares on the kingside. White's bishop looks worse and worse. } ) Nh7 
40. Nf1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6,Gg6f4][%csl Bf4]} 
41. Ng3 Ng6 
42. Nh5 Qh8 
43. Rh3 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8a6]} { White used their knight to stop Black from playing ...Nf4. Now, however, Black can win on the queenside where White has no defenses. } 
44. Bc2 Qa6 {[%csl Ra2,Rc4]} 
45. Bb3 Qa3 {[%cal Ga3b2,Ga7a6,Ga6a5,Gg2f1][%csl Yb3,Yd2,Yg2]} { The engine says Black is +5! Black will either play ...Qb2+ and/or ...a5-a4 and crack White's position.

A brilliant positional game. White never had active play. } 
