1. d4 Nf6 
2. c4 e6 
3. Nc3 Bb4 
4. e3 b6 { In this course, we try to play 4...b6 if possible. } 
5. Nge2 { White wants to defend the knight on c3 with their other knight. } Bb7 
6. a3 Be7 ( { With the white knight on e2 ready to take the place of the other knight, in case of } 6...Bxc3+ { , Black decides to keep the two bishops this time! } ) 
7. d5 { White tries to block the Black bishop on b7. } O-O 
8. g3 { With the white knight on e2, the bishop on f1 cannot move on its own, so White decides to fianchetto instead. } Re8 { Black prepares for the opening of the e-file. } 
9. Bg2 exd5 
10. cxd5 Bf8 {[%cal Be8e1]} 
11. O-O c6 { Attacking the center. } 
12. dxc6?! ( 12.e4 { is a better try for an advantage. } ) dxc6 
13. b4 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge5d3,Ge5c4][%csl Bc4,Bd3,Be5]} { Black has no problems at all, and can play for an advantage now. } 
14. Bb2 Ne5 
15. Qb3 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5]} { This defends the Black bishop on b7, so Black can soon play ...c5. } 
16. Rad1 c5 {[%cal Ge5f3,Gb7g2][%csl Bf3]} { Now White is in trouble since the white squares near the king are weak. } 
17. bxc5?! Nf3+ {[%csl Rg1]} ( 17...Bxg2 18.Kxg2 Qc6+ { is also very strong for Black. } ) 
18. Kh1 Ng4 {[%csl Rh2]} { Black has a very strong attack. } 
19. Nd4? Ngxh2! { Black is completely winning now. Black didn't play the cleanest way afterwards, but still got the job done. } 
20. c6 Bxc6 
21. Nxc6 Qxc6 {[%cal Gc6h1,Gh2f1,Gc6h6,Gh6h1][%csl Rf1,Bf3,Bh2]} 
22. Bxf3 Nxf3 ( { Even better is } 22...Qxf3+! 23.Kxh2 Re5! ) 
23. Qd5 Rac8 ( 23...Qf6! ) 
24. Qxc6 Rxc6 
25. Kg2 Ne5 { Black has an extra pawn and the better position. } 
26. Nb5 Nc4 ( 26...Rc2! ) 
27. Bd4? ( { White should have tried } 27.Nxa7! Rc7 28.Rc1! Nxe3+! 29.fxe3 Rxa7 30.Bd4 { with drawing chances. } ) a6! 
28. Nc3 Bxa3 
29. Nd5 b5 
30. Rh1 Rd6 {[%csl Rd5,Bb5,Ba6]} { Black has two extra passed pawns. White had enough. } 
